nch, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gilbert Hansard IV was born about 1300, in Lincolnshire, England, his father, Sir Robert Hansard, was 30 and his mother, Margaret Redman, was 29. He married Lora in 1316, in South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 26 July 1339, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1300–before 26 July 1339":"umbes 1300–enne 26. juulit 1339","1300–1339":"1300–1339","1289–1349":"1289–1349","1330–1367":"1330–1367","1272–1313":"1272–1313","before 26 July 1339":"enne 26. juulit 1339","1330":"1330","1272":"1272","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1289":"1289","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1300":"umbes 1300","before 24 August 1313":"enne 24. augustit 1313","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1300–before 26 July 1339":"noin 1300–ennen vuotta 26. heinäkuuta 1339","1300–1339":"1300–1339","1289–1349":"1289–1349","1330–1367":"1330–1367","1272–1313":"1272–1313","before 26 July 1339":"ennen vuotta 26. heinäkuuta 1339","1330":"1330","1272":"1272","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1289":"1289","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1300":"noin 1300","before 24 August 1313":"ennen vuotta 24. elokuuta 1313","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1300–before 26 July 1339":"environ 1300–avant 26 juillet 1339","1300–1339":"1300–1339","1289–1349":"1289–1349","1330–1367":"1330–1367","1272–1313":"1272–1313","before 26 July 1339":"avant 26 juillet 1339","1330":"1330","1272":"1272","1316":"1316",